28    /**
29    * Methods necessary for partially or full decomposing an expression. Initially
30    * this is intended to expanded the locations were inlining can occur, but has
31    * other uses as well.
32    *
33    * For example:
34    * var x = y() + z();
35    *
36    * Becomes:
37    * var a = y();
38    * var b = z();
39    * x = a + b;
40    *
41    * @author johnlenz@google.com (John Lenz)
42    */

688    /**
689    * Determine whether a expression is movable, or can be be made movable be
690    * decomposing the containing expression.
691    *
692    * An subExpression is MOVABLE if it can be replaced with a temporary holding
693    * its results and moved to immediately before the root of the expression.
694    * There are three conditions that must be met for this to occur:
695    * 1) There must be a location to inject a statement for the expression. For
696    * example, this condition can not be met if the expression is a loop
697    * condition or CASE condition.
698    * 2) If the expression can be affect by side-effects, there can not be a
699    * side-effect between original location and the expression root.
700    * 3) If the expression has side-effects, there can not be any other
701    * expression that can be effected between the original location and the
702    * expression root.
703    *
704    * An expression is DECOMPOSABLE if it can be rewritten so that an
705    * subExpression is MOVABLE.
706    *
707    * An expression is decomposed by moving any other sub-expressions that
708    * preventing an subExpression from being MOVABLE.
709    *
710    * @return Whether This is a call that can be moved to an new point in the
711    * AST to allow it to be inlined.
712    */

721    /**
722    * Walk the AST from the call site to the expression root and verify that
723    * the portions of the expression that are evaluated before the call are:
724    * 1) Unaffected by the the side-effects, if any, of the call.
725    * 2) That there are no side-effects, that may influence the call.
726    *
727    * For example, if x has side-effects:
728    * a = 1 + x();
729    * the call to x can be moved because "a" final value of a can not be
730    * influenced by x(), but in:
731    * a = b + x();
732    * the call to x can not be moved because the value of b may be modified
733    * by the call to x.
734    *
735    * If x is without side-effects in:
736    * a = b + x();
737    * the call to x can be moved, but in:
738    * a = (b.foo = c) + x();
739    * the call to x can not be moved because the value of b.foo may be referenced
740    * by x(). Note: this is true even if b is a local variable; the object that
741    * b refers to may have a global alias.
742    *
743    * @return UNDECOMPOSABLE if the expression can not be moved, DECOMPOSABLE if
744    * decomposition is required before the expression can be moved, otherwise
745    * MOVABLE.
